{
  "family": "Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag Reaction (Remote Functionalization)",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CCCCN(C)Cl"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "C1CCNC1C"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "O.O=S(=O)(O)O"
    ],
    "rationale": "This is a classic and simple example of the Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag reaction. The reaction starts with N-chloro-N-methylbutan-1-amine. Under acidic conditions (sulfuric acid) and heat/light, a radical rearrangement occurs. The nitrogen-centered radical abstracts a hydrogen atom from the delta-carbon (C4) via a six-membered transition state. The resulting carbon radical then abstracts the chlorine atom from the nitrogen, forming a 4-chloro-N-methylbutan-1-amine intermediate. Subsequent intramolecular nucleophilic substitution (cyclization) upon treatment with base (not explicitly shown as a reagent, but implied in the workup) yields the final product, 1-methylpyrrolidine. This example clearly demonstrates the key C-H activation at a remote (delta) position and subsequent cyclization to form a pyrrolidine ring, which is the hallmark of this reaction.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple acyclic N-chloroamine substrate that cyclizes to a pyrrolidine. It avoids complex structures, arenes, or other functional groups that could overlap with different named reactions. The core transformation is a remote C-H functionalization followed by cyclization, which is specific to the Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag reaction and distinct from reactions like the Beckmann rearrangement (oximes to amides), Hofmann rearrangement (amides to amines), or other radical cyclizations that do not involve this specific N-haloamine precursor and 1,5-hydrogen atom transfer."
  }
}
